<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,690,966]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[402,450,691,715]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">type</typeStatus>
series, this species was described from specimens collected on 
<emphasis box="[1170,1257,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Beginia</emphasis>
sp. [sic], possibly a typographic mistake for 
<taxonomicName box="[494,588,727,750]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[494,588,727,750]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. This dark brown thrips (
<figureCitation box="[911,1055,726,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Figs 
<number box="[969,1055,726,750]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="98.5" valueMax="100.0" valueMin="97.0">97–100</number>
</figureCitation>
) is unusual in having a very long antennal segment III, about 3.5 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[774,860,762,786]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[828,860,762,786]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="98.0">98</number>
</figureCitation>
). Antennal segments III–IV are pale with the apex dark (
<figureCitation box="[219,305,798,822]" captionStart="FIGURES 93 – 101" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 93 – 101. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. striatus female 93 – 96: 93. Dorsal view; 94. Antenna; 95. Mesonotum and metanotum; 96. Pronotum. H. brasiliensis female 97 – 100: 97. Dorsal view; 98. Antenna; 99. Head and pronotum; 100. Mesonotum and metanotum. H. flavidus female: 101. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280422/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Fig. 
<number box="[274,305,798,822]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="98.0">98</number>
</figureCitation>
), and the tibiae are extensively pale. Moreover, the discal setae on abdominal sternites III–VI are placed only laterally and males lack sternal pore plates.
</paragraph>
